'''Thomas Foley''' (c.1670 <U+2013> [[10 December]] [[1737]]) held the sinecure office of [[auditor of the imprests]].  He was the eldest son of [[Paul Foley (ironmaster)|Paul Foley]], [[Speaker of the British House of Commons|Speaker of the House of Commons]] and [[ironmaster]], and succeeded to his estates around [[Stoke Edith]], Herefordshire on his father's death in 1699.  

Thomas Foley was Member of Parliament for [[Hereford (UK Parliament constituency)|Hereford]] from 1700 to 1722 and for [[Stafford (UK Parliament constituency)|Stafford]] from 1722 to 1727 and again from 1734 until his death.  Throughout this period, he was the leading ironmaster in the [[Forest of Dean]].  Initially this business was managed by [[John Wheeler (ironmaster)|John Wheeler]] and then by [[William Rea]], until Rea was sacked in 1725.  From that time the number of ironworks operated by his business, latterly without outside partners gradually declined.  

He and his wife Anne, daughter and heir of Essex Knightley of [[Fawsley]], [[Northamptonshire]] had one son [[Thomas Foley (c 1695-1749)]], and two daughters.  

